### Fetching User Data

After a user logs in, you might want to fetch their data from Cognito to personalize their experience or display specific information. To do this, we'll create a `getUserData` function in our `auth.js` helper file.

<Instruction>Add the following code to the `auth.js` file to implement the `getUserData` function:</Instruction>

```js
export function getUserData() {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const cognitoUser = userPool.getCurrentUser()

    if (cognitoUser) {
      cognitoUser.getSession((err, session) => {
        if (err) {
          reject(err)
          return
        }

        cognitoUser.getUserAttributes((err, attributes) => {
          if (err) {
            reject(err)
            return
          }

          const userData = attributes.reduce((acc, attribute) => {
            acc[attribute.Name] = attribute.Value
            return acc
          }, {})

          resolve(userData)
        })
      })
    } else {
      reject(new Error("No user found"))
    }
  })
}
```

The `getUserData` function checks if there's a currently authenticated user. If so, it fetches the user's session and attributes, converting the attributes into a more convenient JavaScript object. If there's no authenticated user, it rejects the promise with an error.

Now you can use this `getUserData` function in any component that needs to fetch the user's data.

```jsx
